Author definition of units: Fecal compositon (%) of Japanese serow in the western foothills of Mt. Zao, from October 1983 to September 1984.
Author definition of methods: Fecal pelets were collected six times Octrober 1983 and September 1984, and were grouped into four seasons according to plant phenology. Thirty pellets were sampled from each dung pile, represntting each defecation. Six dung piles were sampled in Autumn (Feb/March 1984), four in spring (May/June 1984), and five in summer (September 1984).
Author explaination of grouping: 30 pellets from 6 dung piles sampled
Author explaination of sample size: All grouping sample sizes combined. 30 pellets from each respective number of dung piles sampled from in each of the four seasons.
Reported Study Site Location: north facing slope of Mt. Ryuzan in the western footthills of Mt. Zao

Season in which plant recorded: Cool dry, warm dry, warm wet
Units/metric diet is reported: % diet in GC and FC for pronghorn (I did no include the data for the cattle.)
Author definition of units: Differences between cattle and pronghorn(Antilocapra americana) diets on good (GC) and fair (FC)range conditions in southcentralNew Mexico, USA
Reported Method: Microhistological analyses of fecal samples collected each season within the two range condition classes
Author definition of methods: Diets were determined by micro- histological analyses of pronghorn and cattle fecal samples collected each season within the two range condition classes. At least 100 g of fecal samples were collected immediately after an animal had defecated.
Author explaination of grouping: The GC class is an area under moderate grazing intensity. The fair condition range is an area under heavy grazing intensity.
Author explaination of sample size: At least 100 g of fecal samples were collected immediately after an animal had defecated. In total 30 cattle and 22 pronghorn fecal groups were collected between January and May.
Reported Study Site Location: 32 km north of Las Cruces, New Mexico
Citation (abrv): Clemente, F.; Influence of Range Condition on Pronghorn (Antilocapra americana) and Cattle Diets in Southern New Mexico

Author definition of units: Percent relative density of epidermal cell tissue fragments in feces from adult female pronghorn
Author definition of methods: Fecal pellets (1 pellet/pile) were collected from adult female pronghorn each week during January through March, 2000 and 2001, and randomly assembled into 2 (2001) or 3 (2000) monthly composites of 12 pellets each.
Author explaination of grouping: percent relative density of plants throughout these months
Author explaination of sample size: 3 composites of 12 pellets per month during 2000 and 2 composites per month during 2001. Winter means were based on all 15 composites.
Reported Study Site Location: Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming, and adjacent areas of Montana
Author reported habitat/biome: range for pronghorn was primarily open grasslandsagebrush steppe with interspersed upland grasslands, wet meadows, old agricultural fields and pastures, agricultural fields on private land, and nonvegetated areas
Citation (abrv): Sylvanna J. Boccadori, P. J. White, Robert A. Garrott, John J. Borkowski, Troy L. Davis, Yellowstone Pronghorn Alter Resource Selection After Sagebrush Decline, Journal of Mammalogy, Volume 89, Issue 4, 15 August 2008, Pages 10311040, https://doi.org/10.1644/07-MAMM-A-173.1

Author definition of units: Food plant species in the diet of wild ungulates
Author definition of methods: micro-histological analysis of dung and its comparison with reference slides of plant species available in the area
Author explaination of grouping: The authors organized the groupings by ungulate. There are Sambar, Tahr, Blue Sheep, HMD, Livestock, and Both Groups.

Reported Study Site Location: Bedini-Ali and Tungnath regions of Uttarakhand

Author definition of units: Comparison of the diets of male antelope in southwestern Utah for seven periods throughout the summer months as determined by four methods. Rumen, intestinal feces, site feces, utilization, (and the mean of all four is the last column of the graph.)
Author definition of methods: Rumen and fecal materials were obtained from the killed animals by sampling the contents of the rumen and rectum. Two animals were taken each month from July to November in 1970, and in 197I two animals were killed in April and two in June. Four different sources of data were thus available for comparison: rumen material, intestinal feces, feces collected from the ground, and vegetation estimates.
Author explaination of grouping: The study was done in two phases. One involved killing pronghorn antelope from an experimental herd confined within an enclosure on the Desert Experimental Range in southwestern Utah, a branch of the Intermountain Forest and Range Experiment Station, U.S. Forest Service.
Author explaination of sample size: Two animals were taken each month from July to November in 1970, and in197 I two animals were killed in April and two in June.
Reported Study Site Location: Desert Experimental Range of Intermountain Forest and Range Experimentation Station, Utah
Reason for confidence level?: unsure of my interpretation of data

Author definition of units: Percentage composition of food items in 42 antelope rumen samples, collected during the hunting season, October 30- November 3, 1970
Author definition of methods: Analysis of rumen contents. The composition of dried samples was calculated in terms of percent by weight to 1 percent accuracy. Items of less than 1 percent were recorded as traces.
Author explaination of grouping: "the winter period" Curing the pronghorn hunting season in early november, 1960, samples of the rumen contents of 42 pronghorns were obtained from hunters in various parts of the range exclusive of the study area. These samples were intermediate in composition between the fall and winter periods but approached the winter diet.
Author explaination of sample size: 42 pronghorns obtained from hunters during hunting season
Reported Study Site Location: Matador, Cypress Hill
